<h3><a name="A_Message_about_Securing_Sensitive_Data"></a>A
Message
about Securing Sensitive Data from BSICS Computing Support</h3>
<br>
<h4>Securing Your Sensitive Data</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">In
February, Executive Vince
Chancellor Gottfredson sent an email to the campus community
&nbsp;regarding the need to evaluate and protect sensitive data
stored
on computers, other electronic devices, and in paper form.<br>
Information that can be used for identity theft remains a particular
concern. This includes names in combination with any of the <br>
following:<br>
</div>
<ul style="margin-left: 40px;">
  <li>&nbsp;Social Security
numbers (SSNs),</li>
  <li>&nbsp;Driver's license
or State-issued identification card numbers,</li>
  <li>&nbsp;Individuals'
financial account, credit card, or debit card numbers,</li>
  <li>&nbsp;Electronic medical
or health insurance information.</li>
</ul>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">If&nbsp;you
must store sensitive data, electronically or on paper,
please make BSICS Computing Support aware of it.
&nbsp;Either send email&nbsp;to <a href="mailto:helpdesk@ics.uci.edu">helpdesk</a>
or&nbsp;directly to the BSICS Director of Computing Support, Bill
Cohen,&nbsp; at <a href="mailto:wdcohne@ics.uci.edu">&lt;wdcohen@ics.uci.edu&gt;&nbsp;</a>.<br>
<br>
Additional information on securing computers and data is available on
UCI's "Safe
Computing" Web site: &nbsp;<a class="moz-txt-link-freetext"
 href="http://security.uci.edu/">http://security.uci.edu</a>
</div>
<h4>UCI Online Information
Security Tutorial</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">In
late March, &nbsp;Dana Roode and
Mark Askren announce the availability of a new tool to help you keep
information and computers safe: the UCI online "Information Security"
tutorial. &nbsp;All faculty and staff are encouraged to take the
tutorial. &nbsp;To do so log into TED (<a
 class="moz-txt-link-abbreviated" href="http://www.ted.uci.edu/">www.ted.uci.edu</a>),
click on the "Catalog and Enrollment" tab, and scroll down to the
course
labeled "Information Security."<br>
</div>
<br>
<br>
<hr style="width: 100%; height: 2px;">
<h3><a name="BSICS_Anti_Virus"></a>Computer
Security</h3>
<br>
The following are some of the campus and schoolwide computer security
services that NACS and BSICS Computing Support provide to keep your
computer and your data safe. &nbsp;The provided services, these and
others, are by no means impenetrable and all users must keep in mind
safe computing practices at all times. &nbsp; The &nbsp;UCI:
Safe Computing website (<a href="http://security.uci.edu">http://security.uci.edu</a>)
has additional information and tips on safe computing.
<h4>Campus Firewall</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">NACS&nbsp;
provides a campus firewall that can block&nbsp;connections
to to any campus IP address from off campus. &nbsp;BSICS Computing
Support maintains the server registration table&nbsp; for all hosts
in
BSICS IP address space. &nbsp;Enabling off campus access to any
host is
as simple as emailing BSICS Computing Support.<br>
</div>
<br>
<h4>Email Scanning</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">BSICS
and NACS&nbsp;use Mailscanner and Spam Assassin to scan all
incoming and outgoing email messages for viruses and spam.
&nbsp;When a
virus is found, the email is returned to sender. &nbsp;For spam, a
"spam score" is added. &nbsp;Users can use the mailboss web
application
(<a href="https://mailboss.ics.uci.edu">&nbsp;https://mailboss.ics.uci.edu</a>)
to filter spam and set up white lists for their BSICS email.<br>
</div>
<br>
<h4>Security
Scanner</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">NACS provides a tool to scan
BSICS networks for potential computing vulnerabilities. &nbsp;Support
reviews and repairs vulnerabilities regularly on supported hosts.&nbsp;
&nbsp;Owners of unsupported hosts will recieve notification when
vulnerabilities are detected. &nbsp; A quick response to any
vulnerability notification will be ensure the
safety
of the network and prevent the possible loss of connectivity.
&nbsp;<br>
</div>
<br>
<h4>AntiVirus</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">Sophos
Windows and Macintosh Anti-virus programs are available for all of the
school's affiliates. &nbsp;The only requirement is an ICS login to
download and update the program. &nbsp;For instructions on how to
install it on your laptop
or desktop computer, please see:
<br>
<br>
<a class="moz-txt-link-freetext"
 href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/computing/faculty/sophos_remoteupd.php">http://www.ics.uci.edu/computing/faculty/sophos_remoteupd.php</a><br>
<br>
<br>
</div>
<br>
<hr style="width: 100%; height: 2px;">
<h3><a name="Other_BSICS_News"></a>Other
&nbsp;BSICS News</h3>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><a name="New_CUPS_Server"></a>New
CUPS Print Server</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;">This
quarter will see the upgrade of BSICS printing to CUPS as the
replace for the LPRng print server. &nbsp;The CUPS server has been
adopted as the printing standard by many operating systems&nbsp;and
offers improved printing support for more of the printer models
available than our current LPRng &nbsp;printserver. &nbsp;<br>
<br>
CUPS provides support both Internet Printing Protocol(IPP) and LPR
printing protocols. &nbsp;IPP&nbsp; has been incorporated into
Macs, Windows, Unix and Linux variants. &nbsp;Adding a printer on
these operating systems is as simple as knowing the name of the
printserver and the printer.&nbsp;There is no longer a need for
complex printcap files as was needed in the past with LPRng. &nbsp;<br>
<br>
Look for a full set of instructions on adding and configuring printers
for supported and unsupported ICS hosts coming soon. &nbsp;Advanced
users can start using CUPS now. &nbsp;Just set your ServerName to
printserver.ics.uci.edu in a client.conf and you're off.<br>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><a
 name="Database_Server_and_Management_Tools"></a>MySQL
Database
Server and Management Tools</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;">Computing
Support offers hosting of&nbsp; MySQL Databases.
&nbsp;The school has a shared database server where nominally sized
databases can be stored. &nbsp;For high transaction databases,
or&nbsp; specific needs, computing support can&nbsp;run MySQL
for supported platforms on provided hardware.<br>
<br>
In addition to other opensource tools available at
<a href="http://forge.mysql.com">http://forge.mysql.com</a>
and other places on the web, &nbsp;Computing
Support&nbsp;provides a phpMyAdmin inteface
to manage databases. &nbsp;Please contact helpdesk if you would like
more information on using the phpMyAdmin interfaces.<br>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><a name="CentOs_5_Support"></a>CentOs
5 Support</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;">BSICS
Computing Support &nbsp;is now&nbsp; supporting
&nbsp;on the CentOS 5 release of the Linux operating system.
&nbsp;CentOS 5 is based on the&nbsp; Redhat Enterprise 5
release of a Linux. &nbsp; The decision was made to go with a
RedHat clone due to the overwhelming cost of licensing Redhat
Enterprise on some three hundred Linux nodes currently running in the
clusters at BSICS.<br>
<br>
Support of the CentOS operating system gives us the
opportunity to develop a core infrastructure around the Redhat
Enterprise line of products and the capacity to quickly
assimilate&nbsp;any&nbsp;specialized piece hardware requiring
Redhat Enterprise.<br>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><a name="Conference_Registration"></a>Conference
Registration</h4>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">BSICS
Computing support can host&nbsp; conference registration
pages.&nbsp; A web application will allow you to design a single
page
registration page, including the use of templates and/or
style sheets.&nbsp;&nbsp; The registrants will complete
registration
on-line including payment via credit cards.&nbsp; The payments are
applied directly to UCI revenue accounts specified by your analyst.
&nbsp;The management interface allows the&nbsp;download
of&nbsp; registrant
information directly to Excel.
<br>
<br>
</div>
</div>
